On these occasions, the knights assembled in the temple of Mars without the walls, and rode through the principal streets to the Capitol, defiling by the censore, who sat in front of the temple of Castor in the Forum, and saluting them as they passed. Augustus revived this ancient custom which had fallen into disuse: Suet. ii, 38. After it had flourished for a few years, the emperors assumed the censorial office among others, but neglected its duties; and the practice was soon finally dropped. MRC. GIF. s. Liv. ix, 46; Dionys.
